    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-07-24T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-07-24T10:00:00-05:00" n="107"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d107">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.60A/7–2445: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hurley</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-07-24T11:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">July</hi> 24, 1945—11 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1132. Department desires that you approach the Chinese Government at your
                    discretion to prevent employment of German technicians. (ReEmbs despatch #32,
                    June 30, 1945<note n="77" xml:id="d107fn77">Not printed.</note>). Accepted
                    policy of the United Nations is to keep enemy technicians idle and to prepare
                    for repatriation when possible. We understand desire of Chinese industrialists
                        <pb facs="0152" n="142" xml:id="pg_142"/> and authorities in using
                    assistance of German technicians, but in order to achieve a common policy and
                    mutual understanding, such personnel should not be used regardless of how
                    innocent or locally beneficial such services may appear. Other United Nations
                    are cooperating in this policy and it is hoped that Chinese Government will lend
                    its support in making this policy unanimous.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
